text:
<https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2001365512/israel-launches-app-alerting-users-of-exposure-to-coronavirus|https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2001365512/israel-launches-app-alerting-users-of-exposure-to-coronavirus>

It reports: “This app, available for both Android and iOS, works by collecting the GPS and SSID (WiFi network) information of a user's mobile device throughout the day. This data is saved only on the mobile device and is not transmitted to the Ministry of Health, other government agencies, or any organization.”

Loading data
The app acquires its data at patients’ examination desks. The Israeli health ministry says that after questioning the patient about his or her movements, all the details are captured and loaded onto JavaScript Object Notation (JSON)-which stores simple data structures and objects and is basically used in transmitting data between a web application and a server.
The ministry says that such data will be captured every hour to ensure that the app is updated.

Getting notified
The app will read and match the details and locations before relaying the findings on whether the user has been exposed or not.
“When using the app, it will compare your data to the data in the downloaded JSON file and if the app detects that you were exposed to a known Coronavirus patient, it will alert you with a message stating that a match was found,” Bleeping Computer notes.

I wanted to propose a no-code solution for the self-report data collection. Given that we are collecting potentially sensitive data, going with an established platform seems safer than DIY.

For form building, I would recommend TypeForm (<https://www.typeform.com/templates/>) and something like AirTable (<https://airtable.com/>) for aggregating/analyzing the data. For API integrations, Zapier has a lot of connectors (<https://zapier.com/apps/integrations>).
